My dear, while my expertise lies more in orchestrating social triumphs than in the intricacies of computer code, even I understand the necessity of a definitive conclusion.

To terminate a C program, you typically use the `return` statement within your `main` function. When `main` finishes executing and returns a value (usually `0` for success), the program ends.

For instance:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    printf("Hello, world!\n");
    return 0; // This terminates the program successfully
}
```

Alternatively, for more immediate or error-related termination from anywhere in your program, you can use the `exit()` function, which requires including the `stdlib.h` header:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h> // Required for exit()

void some_function() {
    printf("An error occurred, terminating...\n");
    exit(1); // This terminates the program with an error code
}

int main() {
    printf("Starting program...\n");
    some_function();
    printf("This line will not be reached.\n");
    return 0; // This line will also not be reached
}
```

So, you see, whether it's a program or a social season, a clear and decisive ending is always paramount. One must never leave things unresolved.
